ng_explanation>\"\n        \"findings\": \"[{\"summary\":\"<insight_1_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_1_explanation\"}, {\"summary\":\"<insight_2_summary>\", \"explanation\": \"<insight_2_explanation\"}]\"\n    }\n\n# Grounding Rules\nAfter each paragraph, add data record reference if the content of the paragraph was derived from one or more data records. Reference is in the format of [records: <record_source> (<record_id_list>, ...<record_source> (<record_id_list>)]. If there are more than 10 data records, show the top 10 most relevant records.\nEach paragraph should contain multiple sentences of explanation and concrete examples with specific named entities. All paragraphs must have these references at the start and end. Use \"NONE\" if there are no related roles or records. Everything should be in English.\n\nExample paragraph with references added:\nThis is a paragraph of the output text [records: Entities (1, 2, 3), Claims (2, 5), Relationships (10, 12)]\n\n# Example Input\n-----------\nText:\n\nEntities\n\nid,entity,description\n5,ABILA CITY PARK,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n\nRelationships\n\nid,source,target,description\n37,ABILA CITY PARK,POK RALLY,Abila City Park is the location of the POK rally\n38,ABILA CITY PARK,POK,POK is holding a rally in Abila City Park\n39,ABILA CITY PARK,POKRALLY,The POKRally is taking place at Abila City Park\n40,ABILA CITY PARK,CENTRAL BULLETIN,Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park\n\nOutput:\n{\n    \"title\": \"Abila City Park and POK Rally\",\n    \"summary\": \"The community revolves around the Abila City Park, which is the location of the POK rally. The park has relationships with POK, POKRALLY, and Central Bulletin, all\nof which are associated with the rally event.\",\n    \"rating\": 5.0,\n    \"rating_explanation\": \"The impact rating is moderate due to the potential for unrest or conflict during the POK rally.\",\n    \"findings\": [\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Abila City Park as the central location\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Abila City Park is the central entity in this community, serving as the location for the POK rally. This park is the common link between all other\nentities, suggesting its significance in the community. The park's association with the rally could potentially lead to issues such as public disorder or conflict, depending on the\nnature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. [records: Entities (5), Relationships (37, 38, 39, 40)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POK's role in the community\",\n            \"explanation\": \"POK is another key entity in this community, being the organizer of the rally at Abila City Park. The nature of POK and its rally could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on their objectives and the reactions they provoke. The relationship between POK and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this community.\n[records: Relationships (38)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"POKRALLY as a significant event\",\n            \"explanation\": \"The POKRALLY is a significant event taking place at Abila City Park. This event is a key factor in the community's dynamics and could be a potential\nsource of threat, depending on the nature of the rally and the reactions it provokes. The relationship between the rally and the park is crucial in understanding the dynamics of this\ncommunity. [records: Relationships (39)]\"\n        },\n        {\n            \"summary\": \"Role of Central Bulletin\",\n            \"explanation\": \"Central Bulletin is reporting on the POK rally taking place in Abila City Park. This suggests that the event has attracted media attention, which could\namplify its impact on the community. The role of Central Bulletin could be significant in shaping public perception of the event and the entities involved. [records: Relationships\n(40)]\"\n        }\n    ]\n\n}\n\n# Real Data\n\nUse the following text for your answer. Do not make anything up in your answer.\n\nText:\n----Reports-----\nid,full_content\r\n6,\"# AI Technology in Academic Publishing\n\nThe community centers around AI TECHNOLOGY, which interacts with multiple stakeholders including AUTHORS, EDITORS, PEER REVIEWERS, and PUBLISHERS. Key relationships include the requirement for disclosure, ethical use, transparency, and responsibility in manuscript preparation, peer review, and research design. The integration of AI into academic publishing is governed by policies that emphasize human oversight, originality, and integrity.\n\n## AI TECHNOLOGY as a central entity in academic publishing\n\nAI TECHNOLOGY is a central entity in academic publishing, influencing various aspects such as manuscript preparation, peer review, and research design. It is defined as systems or tools that assist with tasks like writing, editing, data analysis, and content generation. These systems, such as ChatGPT or Large Language Models (LLMs), are widely used but must be disclosed in academic submissions. Their use requires responsible application and human oversight to ensure ethical and transparent practices [records: Entities (4), Relationships (35, 41, 50, 71, 76)].\n\n## Authorship and AI technology\n\nAI technology cannot be listed as authors in academic publications, as authorship requires accountability, responsibility, and adherence to ethical standards. This principle is consistently emphasized across multiple descriptions, highlighting that AI lacks legal standing and the ability to assume responsibility for errors. Authors must maintain full control over their work, ensuring that AI tools do not replace core research responsibilities or compromise the integrity of the research process [records: Relationships (33, 122, 150)].\n\n## Disclosure requirements for AI usage\n\nAuthors must disclose the use of AI technology in their manuscripts, including details such as the model name, version, and manufacturer, as well as the specific systems used and their roles in the research process. This disclosure requirement applies to all instances where AI technologies are utilized in manuscripts, ensuring transparency and accountability in academic publishing. The entity \"\"\n\n## Ethical use and transparency in AI applications\n\nThe ethical use of AI technology requires adherence to principles such as transparency, accuracy, and avoiding bias. AI must be used responsibly, with human oversight to ensure accuracy and avoid bias, while maintaining research integrity and avoiding plagiarism or fabrication. Ethical use also involves following guidelines on transparency, content attribution, and responsible deployment, ensuring that its application supports the values of academic publishing and technological governance. These requirements collectively emphasize the importance of ethical frameworks in guiding the development and implementation of AI technologies within academic and professional contexts [records: Relationships (32, 31, 51, 52)].\n\n## AI in peer review and editorial processes\n\nAI technology is subject to specific restrictions in the context of the peer review process. Peer reviewers are generally prohibited from using AI tools during the peer review process due to concerns related to confidentiality and copyright. However, they may utilize AI technology in the final preparation of referee reports, provided that they disclose such use. Additionally, AI technology must not influence editorial decisions, which must be made by humans to maintain accountability and fairness. These policies reflect a cautious approach to integrating AI into scholarly evaluation, balancing the potential benefits of AI assistance with the need to maintain integrity, transparency, and ethical standards in the peer review system [records: Relationships (41, 36, 53, 40)].\n\n## Data handling and AI\n\nThe entity \"\"\n\n## Research design and AI\n\nThe \"\"\n\n## AI and originality in academic work\n\nAI technology is generally recognized as incapable of producing original work that meets the standards of academic publishing. As such, it is emphasized that AI technology must not compromise the originality of academic work, and authors are required to verify the authenticity of content they produce. Furthermore, authors must ensure that their content remains unique, reinforcing the importance of human oversight in maintaining the integrity and originality of academic output. This highlights the tension between leveraging AI capabilities and preserving the primacy of human agency in research design and content creation [records: Relationships (37, 71, 122)].\n\n## AI and plagiarism detection\n\nAI technology plays a significant role in the academic publishing ecosystem, particularly in the context of plagiarism detection. It can assist in identifying instances of plagiarism, thereby supporting the integrity of scholarly work. However, the responsibility for ensuring the originality of their work ultimately rests with the authors. Furthermore, AI technology must be used ethically and appropriately, with strict adherence to guidelines that prevent its misuse in ways that could lead to plagiarism or the misrepresentation of content. The interplay between AI technology and plagiarism highlights the need for clear policies and accountability mechanisms within academic publishing systems [records: Relationships (38, 411)].\n\n## AI and image generation\n\nAI technology includes image generators like Midjourney or DALL-E, which are prohibited in submitted manuscripts. Image creation using AI tools is restricted and requires proper labeling and citation. This reflects a growing concern about the use of AI-generated images in academic publishing, where the authenticity and originality of visual content must be maintained. Publishers and journals have established policies to ensure that AI-generated images are clearly identified and properly cited, preventing the misrepresentation of visual data in scholarly work [records: Relationships (47, 66)].\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n3,GENERATIVE AI,\"Generative AI refers to a category of artificial intelligence technology capable of creating new content, including text, images, videos, code, data, and other forms of media, based on user input or training data. This type of AI is widely used in academic research, manuscript preparation, and publishing processes. However, its use is subject to specific disclosure requirements when employed in academic work, submissions, or research. Generative AI may introduce inaccuracies, biases, or other issues if not used responsibly, and certain aspects of its application are restricted in academic publishing, particularly in the preparation of manuscripts and peer review processes. Some publishers, such as Elsevier, have implemented restrictions on the use of Generative AI for substantially writing manuscripts. Despite these limitations, Generative AI remains a significant tool in academic contexts, often utilized for content creation, data generation, and other research-related tasks. Its integration into academic workflows continues to raise important questions about authorship, accountability, and ethical use in scholarly communication.\",24\r\n6,LLM,\"Large language models (LLMs) are a subset of AI technology capable of generating human-like text, and in some cases, images and other forms of content. They are used in various aspects of academic writing, research, and manuscript preparation, including tasks such as text generation, language improvement, grammar correction, and data creation. LLMs, such as ChatGPT or DALL-E, are considered a type of generative AI that can produce text, code, and other content based on prompts. Their use in academic contexts is subject to disclosure requirements, with specific guidelines varying by publisher. For instance, Elsevier restricts the use of LLMs from substantially writing manuscripts, while Emerald imposes restrictions on their use during the peer review process. Additionally, LLMs are often used for editing and enhancing written content but are generally not intended for generating original research data. The extent of disclosure required depends on the impact of the LLM on the manuscript, with some institutions mandating transparency when these tools are employed in academic work.\",15\r\n46,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,\"The process of manuscript preparation involves creating, refining, and formatting a scholarly work for submission to a journal. This process may incorporate AI-assisted tools, including AI for copy-editing, citation management, and language refinement. However, the use of such tools must be disclosed, and the content must maintain originality. While some descriptions mention the potential use of large language models (LLMs) and generative AI, others clarify that AI should not be used for content creation but rather for editing and formatting. Transparency in the use of AI tools is emphasized across multiple descriptions, highlighting the importance of ethical and responsible integration of technology in academic writing. The overall goal is to ensure that the manuscript meets the standards of academic integrity while leveraging technological advancements where appropriate.\",10\r\n93,CODE CREATION,\"CODE CREATION refers to the process of generating computer code for research purposes, often utilizing generative AI tools. This task involves the use of AI systems to produce code based on prompts provided by authors or researchers. Depending on the context and institutional policies, the use of AI in this process may require disclosure to ensure transparency and adherence to ethical and academic standards. CODE CREATION highlights the intersection of artificial intelligence and academic research, where AI tools are increasingly employed to support or automate coding tasks, raising important questions about authorship, accountability, and the role of AI in scholarly work.\",2\r\n1,ASHA,\"An organization that publishes journals and has specific policies on the use of artificial intelligence in manuscripts\"\"\",2\r\n130,ATTRIBUTION,\"The practice of properly citing sources, ideas, or quotes in scholarly work, which is often lacking in Generative AI outputs\"\"\",1\r\n131,INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RISK,\"A risk associated with Generative AI tools, where the use of these tools may lead to unauthorized reuse of input or output data, potentially infringing on authors' or publishers' rights\"\"\",1\r\n150,RESPONSE,\"The output generated by an LLM in response to a prompt, which should be documented in the manuscript or appendix\"\"\",1\r\n88,TOOL,\"The entity \"\"TOOL\"\" refers to a software or system designed to assist in various aspects of academic manuscript preparation and editing. It may include AI-based tools for tasks such as copy-editing, text generation, image creation, and data analysis. These tools are intended to support researchers and scholars in enhancing the quality and efficiency of their work, with a particular emphasis on leveraging artificial intelligence to automate or augment specific functions within the academic publishing process.\",4\r\n92,DATA VISUALISATION,\"A method of representing data visually, which may involve the use of AI tools to enhance clarity and accessibility\"\"\",1\r\n\n\n-----Relationships-----\nhuman_readable_id,source,target,description,rank\r\n10,GENERATIVE AI,AUTHOR,\"The author is responsible for the ethical and accurate use of generative AI tools in their academic work, including ensuring the originality and integrity of their submissions. Authors must disclose the use of generative AI in their manuscripts, reflecting a shared responsibility between authors and generative AI systems in maintaining scholarly standards and transparency.\",83\r\n96,LLM,AUTHOR,\"Authors use LLMs to generate hypotheses or create data for analysis in their papers, requiring proper citation and disclosure\",74\r\n12,GENERATIVE AI,AI TECHNOLOGY,\"Generative AI is a type of AI technology that can create content, such as text, images, or code, based on user input. As a subset of AI technology, it is designed to generate new and original outputs rather than simply analyzing or processing existing data. This category of AI technology is characterized by its ability to produce creative or synthetic content, making it distinct from other forms of artificial intelligence that may focus on pattern recognition, decision-making, or automation. The descriptions collectively highlight the core functionality of Generative AI within the broader landscape of AI technology, emphasizing its role in content creation and its responsiveness to user-driven inputs.\",72\r\n142,AUTHOR,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,\"Authors may use AI tools during manuscript preparation, but must disclose their use\",69\r\n56,AI TECHNOLOGY,LLM,\"AI technology encompasses a broad range of systems and methods designed to simulate human intelligence, while Large Language Models (LLMs) represent a specific subset of AI technology. LLMs are advanced computational models capable of generating human-like text, and they are commonly used in research and writing applications. In academic contexts, LLMs are particularly relevant for tasks such as text generation, and their use in manuscript preparation must be disclosed to ensure transparency and ethical integrity. As a category of AI technology, LLMs play an important role in the evolving landscape of academic publishing, where the integration of AI tools raises questions about authorship, originality, and accountability. The relationship between AI technology and LLMs highlights the growing influence of artificial intelligence in scholarly communication and the need for clear guidelines governing their use.\",63\r\n133,AUTHOR,CODE CREATION,\"Authors may use AI tools for code creation, but must disclose this use and ensure the code's accuracy and originality\",61\r\n30,GENERATIVE AI,AI POLICY,\"The AI policy sets guidelines for the use of Generative AI tools, emphasizing transparency, accountability, and ethical considerations\",59\r\n69,AI TECHNOLOGY,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,\"AI TECHNOLOGY and MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION are interconnected in the context of academic publishing, where AI technologies may assist in the preparation of manuscripts, particularly through the use of AI-assisted tools for copy editing. However, these tools are generally not employed for generating new content, such as through generative AI models. The use of AI in manuscript preparation necessitates proper disclosure to ensure transparency and maintain academic integrity. Human oversight remains a critical component of the process, ensuring that AI tools are used appropriately and ethically. All instances of AI-assisted manuscript preparation must be disclosed, reflecting a commitment to accountability and adherence to evolving standards in AI governance within academic publishing.\",58\r\n13,GENERATIVE AI,PEER REVIEW PROCESS,\"The use of **GENERATIVE AI** in the **PEER REVIEW PROCESS** is subject to specific guidelines. While **GENERATIVE AI** may be employed by peer reviewers to enhance language quality, it is explicitly prohibited from generating content. Additionally, peer reviewers are advised not to upload unpublished manuscripts into **GENERATIVE AI** tools to maintain confidentiality and data security. Improper use of **GENERATIVE AI** in the **PEER REVIEW PROCESS** may pose risks to the integrity of the review, particularly concerning issues of confidentiality and data protection. These policies aim to harness the benefits of **GENERATIVE AI** while safeguarding the ethical and procedural standards of academic publishing.\",56\r\n28,GENERATIVE AI,DISCLOSURE,\"Authors must disclose the use of Generative AI tools, including the specific tool, its function, and the reason for its use\",52\r\n14,GENERATIVE AI,MANUSCRIPT,\"Generative AI may be used to create or enhance content in a manuscript, which must be disclosed, and it may also be used for copy editing, though not for creating original content, which similarly requires disclosure. These guidelines apply to the use of Generative AI in relation to Manuscript development, emphasizing transparency and accountability in the integration of AI technologies within academic publishing processes.\",49\r\n92,LLM,ETHICAL USE,Large Language Models must be used ethically in the preparation of manuscripts,46\r\n93,LLM,DISCLOSURE,Large Language Models must be disclosed when used in manuscript preparation,43\r\n91,LLM,TRANSPARENCY,Large Language Models must be used transparently in the preparation of manuscripts,41\r\n27,GENERATIVE AI,EDITORIAL DECISION,\"Generative AI tools may influence editorial decisions if used without proper oversight, leading to potential ethical concerns\",40\r\n95,LLM,MANUSCRIPT,Large language models may be used in the research process and must be disclosed if they significantly affect the manuscript,40\r\n11,GENERATIVE AI,LLM,\"Generative AI and Large Language Models (LLMs) are interrelated forms of artificial intelligence technology, with LLMs representing a specific category within the broader domain of Generative AI. Generative AI encompasses a range of technologies designed to create various types of content, including text, images, and data, while LLMs, such as ChatGPT and DALL-E, are specialized models that focus on generating human-like text and other data formats. Both Generative AI and LLMs are increasingly being utilized in academic contexts, particularly in manuscript preparation, where they assist researchers in drafting, revising, and enhancing scholarly work. LLMs are specifically noted as a form of Generative AI that is particularly well-suited for academic applications due to their ability to process and generate textual content effectively.\",39\r\n15,GENERATIVE AI,TAYLOR & FRANCIS,Taylor & Francis acknowledges the capabilities of Generative AI tools but also highlights the risks associated with their use in academic publishing,38\r\n20,GENERATIVE AI,CONFIDENTIALITY,\"Using Generative AI tools may pose risks to confidentiality, as they may not offer sufficient protection for unpublished manuscript data\",38\r\n94,LLM,AUTHORSHIP,Large Language Models must be used in accordance with authorship guidelines,38\r\n90,LLM,RIGHTS PROTECTION,Large Language Models must not infringe on the rights of authors or publishers,35\r\n234,MANUSCRIPT,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,Manuscript preparation involves using LLMs and following citation guidelines,35\r\n26,GENERATIVE AI,PUBLICATION PROCESS,\"Generative AI tools may impact the publication process if used improperly, leading to potential violations of ethical and policy guidelines\",34\r\n24,GENERATIVE AI,DATA,\"Generative AI tools can produce synthetic data, but Taylor & Francis requires rigorous methodology and transparency to ensure accuracy\",32\r\n25,GENERATIVE AI,RESEARCH DESIGN,\"Generative AI tools should not replace core research design elements, as they lack the ability to assume responsibility for the work\",32\r\n192,PEER REVIEWER,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,Peer reviewers must be aware of the potential use of AI tools in manuscript preparation and assess their impact,32\r\n3,BERA,GENERATIVE AI,\"BERA has guidelines on the ethical use of generative AI in research and publication, emphasizing transparency and accountability\",31\r\n168,EDITOR,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,Editors must be aware of the potential use of AI tools in manuscript preparation and assess their impact,30\r\n29,GENERATIVE AI,COPYRIGHT HOLDER,\"The use of Generative AI tools may affect the rights of the copyright holder, requiring careful consideration of intellectual property protections\",29\r\n209,JOURNAL,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,Journals must be aware of the potential use of AI tools in manuscript preparation and assess their impact,29\r\n17,GENERATIVE AI,BIAS,\"Generative AI tools may introduce bias into content, reflecting the biases present in their training data\",28\r\n22,GENERATIVE AI,IMAGE,\"Generative AI tools can be used to create images, but Taylor & Francis prohibits this practice to maintain the integrity of published content\",28\r\n16,GENERATIVE AI,INACCURACY,\"Generative AI tools can produce inaccurate content due to their statistical nature, making it hard to detect and correct errors\",27\r\n18,GENERATIVE AI,HALLUCINATION,\"Generative AI tools may generate content that is not factually accurate, leading to hallucinations that are difficult to identify\",27\r\n23,GENERATIVE AI,FIGURE,\"Generative AI tools can generate figures, but their use in this context is restricted by Taylor & Francis to prevent unethical practices\",27\r\n80,LANGUAGE MODEL,LLM,\"The term \"\"LLM\"\" stands for \"\"language model,\"\" and it refers to systems such as ChatGPT, which are a specific type of artificial intelligence technology designed for text generation. LLMs are categorized under the broader umbrella of language models, representing advanced AI systems capable of understanding and producing human-like text. These models are widely used in various applications, including but not limited to chatbots, content creation, and natural language processing tasks. The distinction between \"\"language model\"\" and \"\"LLM\"\" is primarily one of scope, with \"\"LLM\"\" often denoting large-scale, deep learning-based language models that have been trained on vast amounts of text data. Both terms are frequently used interchangeably in academic and technical contexts, though \"\"LLM\"\" typically implies a more sophisticated and data-intensive approach to language modeling.\",27\r\n1,ASHA,GENERATIVE AI,\"ASHA has specific policies on the use of generative AI in manuscripts, requiring disclosure and responsibility\",26\r\n0,ANNUALREVIEWS,GENERATIVE AI,Annual Reviews has established policies regarding the use of generative AI in manuscript preparation and submission,25\r\n19,GENERATIVE AI,ATTRIBUTION,\"Generative AI tools often fail to properly attribute ideas, quotes, or citations, which is a standard practice in scholarly work\",25\r\n21,GENERATIVE AI,INTELLECTUAL PROPERTY RISK,\"The use of Generative AI tools may lead to unauthorized reuse of input or output data, potentially infringing on intellectual property rights\",25\r\n89,LLM,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,\"The use of Large Language Models (LLM) in the context of manuscript preparation is multifaceted. While LLMs are employed in the process of preparing manuscripts, their role is constrained to specific functions. Specifically, they may be utilized for AI-assisted copy editing, which involves tasks such as grammar correction, style enhancement, and formatting consistency. However, LLMs are not intended for generating original content, ensuring that the intellectual creation and authorship remain firmly within the domain of human researchers. This distinction underscores the evolving relationship between artificial intelligence and academic publishing, where LLMs serve as supportive tools rather than primary contributors to scholarly work. The interplay between LLMs and manuscript preparation reflects broader discussions in AI governance regarding the ethical and procedural boundaries of AI use in academic contexts.\",25\r\n97,LLM,CITATION,LLMs used in research should be cited in the text of the paper and included in the references,23\r\n99,LLM,DATA,LLMs can generate data that is used for analysis in academic papers,23\r\n98,LLM,REFERENCE,\"References should include detailed information about the LLM used, such as its version and the date of interaction\",22\r\n81,LANGUAGE MODEL,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,\"The use of **LANGUAGE MODEL** in the process of **MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION** is highlighted, as these models are employed to support the creation and refinement of academic manuscripts. Specifically, **LANGUAGE MODEL** may assist in enhancing the linguistic quality of manuscripts, contributing to clearer and more polished written communication. This integration reflects the growing role of artificial intelligence in academic writing processes, where language models serve as tools to improve the overall coherence and readability of scholarly work. The relationship between **LANGUAGE MODEL** and **MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION** underscores the intersection of AI technologies and academic publishing, emphasizing the potential for automation and enhancement in scholarly communication.\",22\r\n100,LLM,RESPONSE,\"An LLM generates a response to a prompt, which may be used in the manuscript or appendix\",16\r\n417,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,TOOL,\"The process of manuscript preparation involves the use of various tools, including AI-based technologies, at different stages of writing and editing. These tools, such as AI-driven copy-editing software, play a significant role in enhancing the efficiency and quality of academic writing. However, their application must be approached with responsibility and awareness of ethical considerations, ensuring that they support rather than undermine the integrity of the scholarly work. The interplay between manuscript preparation and these tools highlights the growing integration of artificial intelligence in academic publishing, reflecting broader trends in AI governance and responsible innovation.\",14\r\n418,MANUSCRIPT PREPARATION,AI ASSISTED COPY EDITING,Manuscript preparation may include AI-assisted copy editing to enhance clarity and readability,13\r\n414,RESEARCH DESIGN,TOOL,\"Research design may involve the use of tools, including AI-based ones, for ideation and planning\",12\r\n2,ASHA,COPE,ASHA references COPE's position statement on AI tools to inform its own policies,9\r\n462,TOOL,CODE CREATION,\"Code creation is a tool used in research, which may involve AI assistance\",6\r\n461,TOOL,DATA VISUALISATION,\"Data visualisation is a tool used to 